## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Race condition fixed** | Original loses items when multiple enqueues happen before `Reset()`. `Channel<T>` handles this correctly. |
| **No forcible kill exists** | `Thread.Abort` has no equivalent. If `Handle()` can hang, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` checkpoints inside it, or move uncooperative work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill`. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. Always `Dispose()` after the thread has stopped. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the top-level loop. Let it propagate elsewhere. |
| **`Thread.Interrupt` doesn't reliably wake `WaitOne`** | Even on Framework it only works in `WaitSleepJoin` state. The `Channel` + `CancellationToken` approach is deterministic. |

---

## Why `Channel<T>` over manual lock + queue

- Thread-safe, allocation-free reads, no manual synchronization
- Built-in backpressure support (bounded channels)
- Native `CancellationToken` support on read/write
- Fixes the lost-signal race in the original `ManualResetEvent` pattern
